### Intro

### Introduction

I began learning about the stock market a year ago.  (so take this blog as  a place to jump start your knowledge, but not as prescription of what you should do with your money). I am sharing my learning with you. 

For those who are getting introduced to these concepts first time, it may not be clear for first time. So don't be overwhelmed. Anything u learn for first time can be overwhelming.

Objective/summary is to explain

1) index funds are best* ( If you already know this,  feel free to skip this blog, unless u r curious about what else i have written about) 

*except for those read a lot and are good controlling their emotions

2) Every investment comes with risk - know what u r doing to avoid costly mistakes and save your money from ignorance

3)  Pros & cons, principles, pitfalls to avoid if you decided to buy (quality ) business rather than taking index fund route

4)  I also gave links to books & articles to interest you further

### Why inveat

#### inflation (capital preservation)

Inflation is the increase in prices for goods and services over time, which reduces the purchasing power of money. For example, today‚Äôs $100 is not the same as $100 in 2014; it buys less now than it did ten years ago.

To preserve your current money, you need to invest it and aim for returns at least equal to the inflation rate. If your money sits idle, you lose purchasing power as prices rise regardless of what you do.

#### capital appreciation

For those seeking financial independence, investing your existing capital at consistent long-term returns helps you reach your goals faster.

### Investment opprtunities and mindset to have

There are numerous ways to invest your money. While I‚Äôll focus on the stock market, here are some other options I‚Äôm aware of:

- Fixed income options:
    - Be aware whether return is going to be greater or lesser than inflation.
    - Bank deposits -
        - get to know how much of your deposit is insured. If your money is not insured, make sure your bank won‚Äôt go bankrupt
    - [**Money Market Funds](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/money-marketfund.asp) (MMF) or [Bonds](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bond.asp)**
        - In USA, Vanguard MMF gives ~ 5.26% yield, Fidelity 4.96% APY
- Stock market
- Real estate
- Commodities like gold
- Bitcoin (?)

Every investment carries some risk of losing money. Sometimes the risk can be very low (e.g., government bonds, especially U.S. bonds, are considered safe and almost risk-free). Nevertheless, risk always exists. Be aware of it.

Investment is all about risk management‚Äîbuying assets that offer the highest possible return for the least risk you‚Äôre willing to accept.

In this digital age, losing your hard-earned money can happen with just one click. Since it‚Äôs all digital, you might not feel the money is gone immediately, but the loss is real. Know the risks of whatever you decide to do with your money.

Preserving ur capital should be foremost priorty. Growing your money can be the second.

Remember once ur money gets halved to 50% due to loss, then u need the investment to return 100% to just break even. So opt for consistent returns rather than high risk high reward investments

Have a long term mindset, Don‚Äôt rush to earn quick money. Usually, that fear of missing out (FOMO) rush will only make you lose money.

Be diversified -  Don‚Äôt put all your eggs in one basket. Diversification ensures that if one investment goes belly up, your life savings are still protected.

Good investment opprotunity should also have less tax burdens when you eventually decide to sell your asset. Also, know the tax implications if you gift the asset to someone else (like your heir).

[Tax deferred investmen](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/taxdeferred.asp)t helps you to compound faster

Note - Dont invest money that u might need within 3-5 years.  The asset you invested in may go down, and you would be forced to sell at a loss. Opt for low-risk investing options like bank deposits or bonds for short-term needs.

### Stock -  Slice of a business rather than a random number generator

The stock market is where people buy and sell businesses, similar to how tomatoes are sold in a vegetable market. A seller quotes a price, and when a buyer agrees, they exchange cash, and the tomato is sold. Stocks are traded similarly via the stock exchange with help of brokerages, with prices fluctuating every microsecond.

Businesses are divided into smaller units called shares or stocks, which are traded because not everyone can afford to buy an entire business.

Share prices are influenced by fear and greed, making them unpredictable in the short term. However, over the long term (5-10 years), stock prices tend to follow the business‚Äôs profits. So, while short-term prices may seem random, they align with business profits over time.

Let me give an example using Amazon. There are 10.39 billion shares of AMZN, currently trading at $177.

Amazon‚Äôs total net profit is $44.4 billion, so profit per share is $4.27. 

As a shareholder, you can expect this $4.27 to be given back to you.( although in reality CEO would try to reinvest a art of 4.27 and grow it to a larger sum and would try to give it back to you at a later time)

Earnings yield is (earnings per share/ share price) * 100%  . Earnings yield is analogous to interest rate on a savings account, showing how much profit you earn for each dollar invested in a company‚Äôs stock.

The earnings yield of AMZN is $4.27 / $177 = 2.41%. So 2.41% of money you invested can be returned to you as part of profit attributable to you. However, with the US government / bank accounts offering a ~5.3% risk-free interest rate, why buy a share, it doesnt make sense right? Let me explain

Look how profit per share went from $2.67 to $11.84. Thats the reason people are ready to buy MSFT share today. Its not today‚Äôs earnings yield they r looking for, instead the one they would be getting after 10 years. So overall MSFT owners beleive by owning shares, they would get more money than what they would get with US gov interest rate. 

This process of estimating future profit and discounting it to today‚Äôs value (because $100 10 years later is less in value today because of inflation) is called Discounted Cash Flow analysis (more on this later). 

In summary:

You own a share, so you can get part of company‚Äôs profit. Even if todays earnings yield is not good, as company grows, you expect higher earning yield for you in future

So important thing to note is, its not enough for a company to be profitable, but it should keep growing its profit, i.e profit should become bigger and bigger 

### Index funds are recommended and buying on ur own stock is hard

For you to make profits, a company should be increasing its profit for the foreseeable future. This means management must be shrewd, the company shouldnot be disrupted by newer technologies, the field should be growing or the company‚Äôs market share within field should be growing etc etc.

How can you be sure a business will grow its profit in the future? You need to understand the business sector, its customers, competitors, and the management team.

You need to read Company‚Äôs 1 annual report, 4 quarterly report, 4 earnings call and much more. And to some extent you need to read about the competitors and customers (if its a B2B)

How do you determine the fair price of a share?

Even after thorough research, what if you make a mistake in your analysis? What if the company loses money, its profit decreases, or remains flat? In these scenarios, you‚Äôre likely to lose money.

Therefore, buying a single business is not recommended. You shouldn‚Äôt put all your eggs in one basket. Depending on who you ask, you might be advised to diversify by buying at least 12 to 50 companies.

It‚Äôs not impossible to research and buy more than 12 companies, but it‚Äôs very challenging. Is it worth your time?

So instead of you having to study about businesses and pick individual business. Genrally buying index funds are recommended

![image.png](https://prod-files-secure.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/936e6585-15b2-4b88-b22a-62a6c58a01c0/417d989e-7990-4b5d-a159-5fce239982e0/image.png)

An index fund is a mutual fund or ETF that aims to mirror the performance of a specific index, like the S&P 500. In the stock market, an index is a statistical tool that measures the performance of a selected group of stocks to assess the overall market or specific sectors. These indices are typically weighted by market capitalization.

S&P 500 index : Tracks 500 of the largest U.S. companies by market capitalization.

**Nifty 50**: Represents the top 50 companies listed on the National Stock Exchange (NSE),

Each quarter, based on changes in market capitalization, companies are [added or removed from the index](https://www.investopedia.com/index-rebalancing-7972596), and weightings within the index are adjusted.

Indices have rules for inclusion and exclusion, so be sure to read them. For instance when I said S&P 500 tracks largest 500 US companies, it was not factually true but more or less true.  once included in the S&P 500, it‚Äôs harder to be removed, only if they meet rules of exclusion, stocks can be removed from S&P 500. So even if a new company grows to become a top 500 business, one company which is already in S&P 500 need to exit to allow space for this new company. And this is fine because, this rule keeps turnover ratio low, hence keeping tax low

Howver Some index rules may seem illogical.. For example, the Dow Jones index includes 30 stocks weighted by stock price, which is meaningless because comparing share prices without considering share count is absurd. Companies can manipulate weightings through [reverse splits](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/reversesplit.asp). Here‚Äôs a [blog](https://erikrood.com/Posts/DJIA.html) for more explanation.

Similarly, Once you understand the Nasdaq-100 inclusion policy, you‚Äôll see it‚Äôs not exactly a tech ETF as commonly believed. The Nasdaq-100 tracks the largest 100 stocks on the Nasdaq exchange. This results in excluding quality tech businesses such as Mastercard, Visa, because they ar enot listed in Nadaq exchange. Additionally, it excludes financial and REIT stocks. Because the Nasdaq-100 excludes many stocks, it is generally not recommended over the S&P 500 or total market index funds.

So always know the rules for inclusion of stock, exlcusion of stock and weightage rule

![image.png](https://prod-files-secure.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/936e6585-15b2-4b88-b22a-62a6c58a01c0/019b502a-8a53-4520-9ddd-a3cb863b3400/image.png)

